{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\nThe `rebar metrics` subcommand: parses `--since/--until` and optional `--bucket day|week|month`, renders the full registry over the range as JSON (default) or a text summary, and is the single entry point wiring the readers.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/_commands/metrics.py` — new: arg parsing + render loop over `src/rebar/metrics/registry.py`.\n- `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py` — register the `metrics` read subcommand in the command-set frozensets and dispatch.\n- `src/rebar/_cli/help/metrics.txt` — new help text.\n- `src/rebar/_cli/help/overview.txt` — add the `metrics` line to the subcommand overview.\n- `tests/golden/cli_help/*.out` — regenerate the overview snapshots (`__overview_help.out`, `__overview_dashhelp.out`) and add `metrics__help.out`, since the subcommand set is enumerated there.\n- `docs/cli-reference.md` — document the command.\n- `tests/interfaces/test_metrics_cli.py` — new CLI subprocess test.\n\n## Approach\nA thin CLI over the registry keeps the command complete-once: it builds a **context object** and calls `rebar.metrics.registry.evaluate(spec, context)` for every `MetricSpec`, emitting value-or-`unavailable` per metric, so new signals appear with no CLI change.\n\n**The context object (the contract the readers already expect):** every reader's registered `compute` is a single-arg callable that reads `ctx.repo_root`, `ctx.since`, `ctx.until` (via `getattr(ctx, \"repo_root\", None)` etc. — see the git/event/sidecar readers). So `metrics.py` constructs a small context (a dataclass or `SimpleNamespace`) carrying exactly `repo_root` (the resolved store root), `since`, and `until` (the parsed range), and passes it to `evaluate`. For `--bucket`, it builds one context per bucket sub-range and evaluates the registry per bucket, keying the output by bucket.\n\n**Adapter isolation (portability guard from 1f77/538c):** `metrics.py` iterates the registry and imports ONLY `rebar.metrics.registry`; it must NOT import `rebar.metrics.adapters.*` (the optional CI/transcript adapters). Registered adapter-backed metrics reach the command only through `REGISTRY`, never a direct import — so the core command stays harness-agnostic.\n\nRegistering a subcommand touches the enumerated help/golden surfaces (`overview.txt` + the `tests/golden/cli_help` snapshots) and the generated `docs/cli-reference.md`, all part of the edit set. Read-only; date bucketing uses the exact HLC wall-clock timestamps; JSON is the default stdout contract, `--output text` a human summary (mirrors `rebar audit`).\n\n## Tests\n- CLI (real subprocess against a temp store): `rebar metrics --since ... --until ... --output json` exits 0 and emits a `metrics` map containing every registered id; an unpopulated metric shows `unavailable`.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `tests/interfaces/test_metrics_cli.py` passes: `rebar metrics --since 2026-01-01 --until 2026-07-01 --output json` exits 0 and the emitted `.metrics` map contains an entry for EVERY id in `rebar.metrics.registry.REGISTRY` (the test asserts `set(output[\"metrics\"].keys()) >= {s.id for s in REGISTRY}` — NOT merely `length > 0`), each entry being either a value (with `source`+`confidence`) or an `unavailable` object.\n- [ ] the portability guard holds: a test asserts `src/rebar/_commands/metrics.py` does not import `rebar.metrics.adapters` (the core command stays harness-agnostic; adapter-backed metrics arrive only via `REGISTRY`).\n- [ ] `rebar metrics --help` renders the help file and the command is listed by bare `rebar` — CLI test asserts exit 0 and help contains `--since`.\n- [ ] the golden CLI-help snapshots are regenerated and the `tests/golden/cli_help` suite passes with `metrics` listed.\n- [ ] `--bucket week` yields a per-bucket series for a metric with history — CLI test asserts the JSON contains at least one bucket key."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784452176510293001,"uuid":"6136a391-a2aa-4b67-a0c1-2d2c6994d159"}